{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616711"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:06:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:06:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16414"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16414"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.16,0.16,0.58,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9105"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74806"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9105"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16414"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60302"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4844"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10378"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21623"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21627"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74806"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old female was brought to a General Practitioner by her sister with concerns of her \u0022not being her usual self\u0022 for the past few months. Her friends noticed she had lost interest in her hobbies and is withdrawn. On the way here, her sister caught her inappropriately touching strangers in public.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common form of young-onset dementia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alzheimer disease","Vascular dementia","Lewy body dementia","Frontotemporal dementia","Wernicke-Korsakoff syndrome"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003EAlzheimer disease\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common form of dementia overall, it is less common in younger patients. In those under 65 years, it accounts for approximately 30% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrontotemporal dementia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common form of young-onset dementia, accounting for about 40% of cases in those under 65 years. It  presents between ages 45-65 with behavioural changes, personality alterations, and language difficulties, rather than the memory problems characteristic of Alzheimer disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVascular dementia\u003C/strong\u003E accounts for about 15% of young-onset dementia cases. It occurs in patients with cardiovascular risk factors and often presents with a stepwise decline in cognitive function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELewy body dementia\u003C/strong\u003E is relatively uncommon in younger patients. It presents in older adults with visual hallucinations, parkinsonism, and fluctuating cognition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWernicke-Korsakoff syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a preventable form of dementia caused by thiamine deficiency, most commonly associated with alcohol use disorder. While it can affect younger patients, it is not one of the more common causes of young-onset dementia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is typical for frontotemporal dementia, with early behavioural changes, disinhibition, and executive dysfunction, while relative preservation of memory is characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Frontotemporal dementia is the most common form of young-onset dementia, typically presenting between ages 45-65 years.","Behavioural changes and language difficulties are the hallmark early symptoms of frontotemporal dementia, rather than memory loss.","Young-onset dementia refers to dementia diagnosed before age 65 years."],"references":["EFERENCES","Gale SA, Acar D, Daffner KR. Dementia. Am J Med. 2018 Oct;131(10):1161-1169. doi: 10.1016/j.amjmed.2018.01.022. Epub 2018 Feb 6. PMID: 29425707","B\u0142aszczyk JW. Pathogenesis of Dementia. Int J Mol Sci. 2022 Dec 29;24(1):543. doi: 10.3390/ijms24010543. PMID: 36613988; PMCID: PMC9820433","Qiu C, De Ronchi D, Fratiglioni L. The epidemiology of the dementias: an update. Curr Opin Psychiatry. 2007 Jul;20(4):380-5. doi: 10.1097/YCO.0b013e32816ebc7b. PMID: 17551353","Dintica CS, Yaffe K. Epidemiology and Risk Factors for Dementia. Psychiatr Clin North Am. 2022 Dec;45(4):677-689. doi: 10.1016/j.psc.2022.07.011. Epub 2022 Oct 14. PMID: 36396272"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60302"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16414"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60302"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T12:59:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T19:00:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9105"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74806"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji